data.title: Jäätteenmäki Not to Stand for Centre Party Leadership
data.meta_description: MEP Anneli Jäätteenmäki will not run as a candidate for leadership of the Centre Party. She announced her decision on Saturday during the YLE current affairs programme Ykkösaamu.
data.text:
”One should not stand for the same post twice,” she said.

Anneli Jäätteenmäki served briefly as Finland's first woman Prime Minister in 2003 and was Chairperson of the Centre Party in 2002-2003. She was compelled to resign over the so-called Iraq papers scandal.

Jäätteenmäki added she wanted to continue her work in the European Parliament.

She gave no indication as to her choice of candidate for the Centre Party leadership. Current runners in the leadership race are Foreign Trade and Development Minister Paavo Väyrynen, Minsiter of Economic Affairs Mauri Pekkarinen, Minister of Public Administration and Local Government Mari Kiviniemi and MP Timo Kaunisto.

The Centre Party will select a new leader at its party conference to be held in June. Its current leader, Prime Minister Matti Vanhanen, announced his intention to step down last December.

Anneli Jätteenmäki also announced she would not stand as a candidate in next year’s Parliamentary Elections. However, she refused to be drawn on whether she might stand as a candidate in the Presidential Election in 2012.
